article.headline: Utah takes advantage of depleted Memphis
article.linkText: Jazz top Grizz to move into West's No. 8 spot
article.story: SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Utah Jazz already outnumbered Memphis from the start, then two Grizzlies were kicked out of the game. And after an emotional lift during a standing ovation for former Jazz great John Stockton as he watched from the crowd, it almost didn't seem fair. The Jazz beat the short-handed Grizzlies 92-81 Monday night, pulling ahead in the race for the final Western Conference playoff berth. "We are still alive and we have maybe a better chance right now than Denver or Portland," said Andrei Kirilenko, who had 17 points and 11 rebounds Monday. By winning the rescheduled game when the rest of the league was idle, the Jazz improved to 41-37 and moved a half-game ahead of Denver (40-37) for the No. 8 spot in the West. Portland (39-37) is a full game back. Utah has made the playoffs 20 straight seasons, and Stockton was part of the last 19 before retiring last summer. He hadn't made a public appearance in Utah since his retirement ceremony until he was caught on camera Monday and shown on the big screen above the court. The fans that showed up on the night of the NCAA basketball championship immediately responded with a standing ovation for the NBA's all-time leader in assists and steals. Although the attendance was well below the announced sellout total of 19,911, the ovation was a loud one. "That's big-time. I got chills when I saw him," said Carlos Arroyo, who has Stockton's old job at point guard and finished with 14 points, seven assists and nine rebounds. "It's a legend, man. A legend. He's great. He's awesome. To see him come back and see the team, that shows a lot of respect." Memphis, which has already clinched its first playoff berth, started the game without Pau Gasol (foot) and Bonzi Wells (back), and by the time it ended the Grizzlies were down to just eight players. Jason Williams was ejected with 15 seconds left in the second quarter for arguing a foul call, and James Posey was thrown out late in the fourth period when he kicked the ball high into the seats after a foul. Gasol, who leads the team in scoring and rebounds, watched helplessly in jeans and a T-shirt from the Grizzlies' bench. He hopes to be back in the lineup within a few days. "Of course I wanted to go, but I have to think long-term, too," Gasol said after the game. Posey led Memphis with 18 points. The game was originally scheduled for Jan. 7, but postponed when the Grizzlies were stuck in Portland during a winter storm. It's a whole lot more crucial now for the Jazz now than it was then because of the playoff race. Utah has four games remaining and -- three against playoff teams. "Now it's the most important games. Maybe it's surprising for such a young team, but I think we've got great characters on this team," said Gordan Giricek, who led the Jazz with 25 points. The Jazz outrebounded the Grizzlies 56-29 to help make up for 37.2 percent shooting (29-78). Mikki Moore had 13 points and 10 rebounds, and Jarron Collins pulled down nine boards for Utah. "What we're hot about -- and I mean hot -- is that we got outrebounded by 27," Memphis coach Hubie Brown said. Lorenzen Wright, who scored 16, cut Utah's lead to 61-57 with a two-handed dunk he punctuated with a scream, then added a layup to cut the margin to two points. But Utah closed the quarter on a 9-2 run to lead 70-61 after three. Earl Watson got the Grizzlies to 80-74 with a layup, but Kirilenko made two free throws, Moore added a basket, and Memphis faltered when Posey was tossed with 2:40 remaining. Giricek made a free throw on the technical and Kirilenko went 1-for-2 on the shots for the foul that led to Posey's punt. < ^Notes@: Brown and Utah's Jerry Sloan are considered among the top contenders for coach of the year. ... The first quarter featured several big scoring runs. Utah scored the first six points, Memphis scored the next 14 and the Jazz responded with the next 10 and led 30-27 entering the second period. ... Sloan's intensity didn't lessen as Utah pulled away late in the third quarter. After a timeout with 16.1 seconds remaining, Sloan directed an expletive at rookie Sasha Pavlovic that was loud and clear from a distance.
